[5] Probable cholera, fatalities - Philippines (Davao del Norte)
Date: Tue 14 Feb 2017
Source: Davao Today [edited]
http://davaotoday.com/main/human-rights/cholera-like-bacteria-found-in-ip-community-in-talaingod/


A team of biologists from the University of the Philippines [UP] conducted a fecalysis last week [week of 6 Feb 2017] in Talaingod, Davao del Norte, and found a cholera-like bacterium which was blamed to be the culprit of an outbreak that claimed lives of several Lumad [indigenous people, IP] last December 2016.

According to Dr Ruth Gamboa, Biology professor from UP Mindanao, their finding was not "conclusive" but pointed out the symptoms such as vomiting and diarrhea of the disease that hit the IP community were similar to that of cholera. "The symptoms were like cholera, but it is still not conclusive for we still need additional laboratory tests," she said. The team's initial findings, Gamboa said, specifically named a water parasite to be the cause of the disease. "Initially, the parasite from their water is normal."

Gamboa added that since 2014, a total of 10 Lumad -- 2 adults and 8 children -- died due to the outbreak when they returned to their community after spending more than a year of refuge in Davao city. In sum, the outbreak already claimed 28 lives since December 2016. Of the 28, 18 were children. Those who died were several Lumad who stayed at the United Church of Christ of the Philippines -- Haran Compound.

"The water here [Davao] is chlorinated, the water in Talaingod is fresh from the spring," Gamboa said referring to what the Lumad told them about the comparison of the water from 2 different sources.

[Byline: Earl O Condeza]

